<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-355-906  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 355 906.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Journal of Systems and Software  Feb 1989 v9 n2 p167(41).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Experimental evaluation of software documentation formats.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sheppard, Sylvia B.; Kruesi-Bailey, Elizabeth; Bailey, John;Boehm-Davis, Deborah A.; Curtis, Bill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Four controlled experiments investigated the effectiveness ofdifferent documentation formats for presenting information aboutcomputer programs.andP;  Nine different documentation formats (somequite novel) were created by varying three different forms ofsymbology (natural language, constrained language, and ideograms)and three different spatial arrangements (sequential, branching,and hierarchical).andP;  Professional programmers used these formats asaid to comprehend (Experiment 1), code (Experiment 2), debug(Experiment 3), and modify (Experiment 4) modular-sized programs.andO;For each programming task, a model of the cognitive activities aprogrammer would perform generated hypotheses about theeffectiveness of different formats.andP;  Natural language was found tobe less effective in assisting most of the tasks studies than aconstrained language or ideograms.andP;  A smaller effect was observed(less frequently than expected) for the spatial arrangement insituations where control flow information aided the task.andP;  Thelargest effect in the experiments, individual differences amongthe participants, accounted for between a third and one-half ofthe variation in performance.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of thepublisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     DocumentationFormatSoftware EngineeringComparisonStudyApplications Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Types of symbology. (table)Types of spatial arrangement. (chart)Example documentation formats. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>